{"title_page": "The Invisible Man (2020 film)", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{short description|2020 film directed by Leigh Whannell}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Invisible Man\n| image          = File:The Invisible Man (2020 film) - release poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Leigh Whannell]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jason Blum]]\n* Kylie du Fresne\n}}\n| writer         = Leigh Whannell\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[The Invisible Man]]''|[[H. G. Wells]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Elisabeth Moss]]\n* [[Aldis Hodge]]\n* [[Storm Reid]]\n* [[Harriet Dyer]]\n* [[Michael Dorman]]\n* [[Oliver Jackson-Cohen]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Benjamin Wallfisch]]\n| cinematography = Stefan Duscio\n| editing        = Andy Canny\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Universal Pictures]]\n* [[Blumhouse Productions]]\n* Nervous Tick\n* [[Goalpost Pictures]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|2|27|Australia|2020|2|28|United States}}\n| runtime        = 124 minutes\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n* Australia\n}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $7 million<ref name=BOM/>\n| gross          = $125.8 million<ref name=NUM>{{cite web |url= https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Invisible-Man-The-(2020)#tab=summary |title=The Invisible Man (2020)|website= [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate= March 20, 2020 }}</ref><ref name=BOM>{{cite web |url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt1051906/?ref_=bo_se_r_1 |title=The Invisible Man (2020)|website= [[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate= March 26, 2020 }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Invisible Man''''' is a 2020 [[Science fiction film|science fiction]] [[Horror film|horror]] [[thriller film]] written and directed by [[Leigh Whannell]]. It follows a woman who believes she is being stalked by her abusive and wealthy boyfriend even after his apparent suicide.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://celebrityinsider.org/invisible-man-pulls-in-a-solid-box-office-weekend-373793/ |title=Invisible Man Pulls In A Solid Box Office Weekend |last=Bridget |first=Hill |date=29 February 2020 |website=celebrityinsider.org |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> She ultimately deduces that he has acquired the ability to become invisible.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2020/02/review-invisible-man-leigh-whannell-elisabeth-moss/607153/ |title=This Time, The Invisible Man Is Really About a Woman |last=David |first=Sims |date=27 February 2020 |website=theatlantic.com |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> The film stars [[Elisabeth Moss]], [[Aldis Hodge]], [[Storm Reid]], [[Harriet Dyer]], [[Michael Dorman]], and [[Oliver Jackson-Cohen]]. It is an international co-production of the United States and Australia.\n\nThe development of a new [[Invisible Man (film series)|''Invisible Man'']] film began as early as 2006. The project was revived as part of Universal's shared cinematic universe in 2016, intended to consist of their classic monsters, with [[Johnny Depp]] attached to star in the title role. After ''[[The Mummy (2017 film)|The Mummy]]'' was released in 2017 to critical and financial failure, development was halted on all projects. In early 2019, the studio changed their plans from a serialized universe to films based on individualized story-telling and the project reentered development. [[Principal photography]] lasted from July to September 2019 in [[Sydney]], Australia.\n\n''The Invisible Man'' was theatrically released in the United States on February 28, 2020, by [[Universal Pictures]]. The film received positive reviews from critics, with praise for Moss' performance, its inventive modernization of the [[The Invisible Man|novel's]] plot, and the combination of scares with \"a smart narrative about how women can be manipulated and abused in harmful relationships\".<ref name=WrapProj/> The film also became a commercial success, grossing $125.8&nbsp;million worldwide against a $7&nbsp;million budget and it is currently the [[2020 in film|fifth highest-grossing film of 2020]]. However, due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] closing theaters across the globe, Universal announced the film would be made available for [[Video on demand|digital rental]] just three weeks after it was released theatrically.\n\n== Plot ==\nTrapped in a violent, controlling relationship with wealthy optics engineer and businessman [[Griffin (The Invisible Man)|Adrian Griffin]] ([[Oliver Jackson-Cohen]]), Cecilia Kass ([[Elisabeth Moss]])\u00a0drugs him with [[Diazepam]] and escapes their home into the nearby woods to wait for her sister, Emily ([[Harriet Dyer]]). After she arrives, Adrian nearly catches Cecilia, but the pair are able to escape.\n\nCecilia hides out with childhood friend, Detective James Lanier ([[Aldis Hodge]]), and his teenage daughter Sydney ([[Storm Reid]]). Two weeks later, Adrian seemingly commits [[suicide]] and leaves Cecilia $5 million in his will handled and organized by his lawyer brother, Tom ([[Michael Dorman]]). As Cecilia tries to move forward, she is plagued by several unexplained experiences. During a job interview, she faints after finding her portfolio's contents removed and is taken to the hospital. Later, the doctor calls and says they found high levels of Diazepam in her system. Shortly after returning home, Cecilia finds the same bottle she drugged Adrian with, which she dropped during her escape, in her bathroom.\n\nShe arranges a meeting with Tom\u00a0and James, insisting that Adrian faked his death and used his optics expertise to become invisible in order to torment her, but gets rebuffed. Cecilia turns to her sister, but Emily refuses to acknowledge her after receiving an email from Cecilia's account stating she never wants to see her again. Later, she is comforted by Sydney, but Sydney is hit by an unseen force, leading her and James to assume Cecilia did it. While a furious James rushes his daughter out of the house, Cecilia tries a number of tactics to catch the figure. After finding Adrian's old phone in the attic and covering the figure with paint, she ends up in a violent struggle before escaping to Adrian's home to investigate. In his lab, she finds a suit that confirms her suspicions. After hiding it in a closet, the invisible figure attacks again, so Cecilia flees and contacts Emily. The pair meet in a restaurant, though as Cecilia begins to tell her what she found, the invisible figure slits Emily's throat with a knife and places it in Cecilia's hand, framing her for the crime.\n\nRemanded to a [[mental hospital]] while she awaits trial, the staff informs Cecilia that she is pregnant. Tom visits her and offers to get her charges dropped if she agrees to \"return to him\" and raise the child, implying that he helped his brother stage his suicide while revealing Adrian tampered with her [[birth control]] to ensure she became pregnant. Cecilia refuses to take the deal and steals a pen from his briefcase. That night, she uses the pen to pretend to commit suicide to draw the invisible figure out. When the figure tries to stop her, she stabs him repeatedly, causing the suit to malfunction. The security team arrives, but the invisible figure violently incapacitates them before fleeing the hospital, with Cecilia in pursuit. Promising not to harm her because of her pregnancy, the figure instead threatens to attack those she loves.\n\nCecilia races to James' house, where she finds the invisible figure attacking him and Sydney. She manages to shoot the figure after spraying him with a fire extinguisher, but when she unmasks him, she finds Tom in the suit. Police find a captive Adrian alive at his house, tied up in his basement and claiming Tom held him prisoner. Cecilia quickly disputes this, insisting the brothers must have shared the suit, with Adrian sending Tom to the house knowing what would happen.\n\nIn an attempt to get Adrian to confess, she meets him at his house to discuss her pregnancy while James listens in on a wire. She agrees to mend their relationship, but only if he confesses to being the invisible figure. Adrian insists Tom did kidnap him, claiming that the experience changed his outlook on life and how he treated her in their relationship. When she begins to cry, Adrian alludes to former abuse using similar phrasing to that of the invisible figure. Smiling, Cecilia departs to use the restroom. Moments later, the room's security camera captures Adrian seemingly committing suicide. Cecilia returns and, apparently distraught, calls the police. Out of the camera's sight however, she silently taunts Adrian; having retrieved the spare suit she hid earlier to kill him.\n\nWhen James arrives and asks what happened, she confirms what the camera saw. He spots the suit in her bag, but accepts her story and allows her to leave. Relieved that she's finally free from Adrian, Cecilia leaves the house with the suit.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Elisabeth Moss]] as Cecilia \"Cee\" Kass\n* [[Oliver Jackson-Cohen]] as [[Griffin (The Invisible Man)|Adrian Griffin]]\n* [[Aldis Hodge]] as James Lanier, a San Francisco police detective, Sydney's father and Cee\u2019s childhood friend\n* [[Storm Reid]] as Sydney Lanier, James' teenage daughter\n* [[Harriet Dyer]] as Emily Kass, Cee\u2019s sister\n* [[Michael Dorman]] as [[Griffin (The Invisible Man)|Tom Griffin]], Adrian's brother and lawyer\n* Benedict Hardie as Marc\n* Amali Golden as Annie\n* Sam Smith as Detective Reckley\n* [[Nash Edgerton]] as a Security Guard\n* Zara Michaels as a Nurse\n* Vivienne Greer as Screaming Woman\n* [[Anthony Brandon Wong]] as Accident Victim\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nDevelopment of a new ''The Invisible Man'' film began as early as 2006 when [[David S. Goyer]] was hired to write the screenplay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstshowing.net/2008/david-s-goyer-directing-the-invisible-man-before-magneto/|title=David S. Goyer Directing The Invisible Man Before Magneto|last=Billington|first=Alex|date=December 12, 2008|website=FirstShowing.net|language=en-US|accessdate=July 15, 2019}}</ref> Goyer remained attached to the project as late as 2011, with little to no further development on the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/david-goyer-invisible-man-remake/|title=David S. Goyer's 'Invisible Man' Remake Is Still Alive|website=screenrant.com|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, the project was announced to be revived as part of Universal's [[cinematic universe]], intended to consist of their [[Universal Classic Monsters|classic monsters]]. [[Johnny Depp]] was cast as the titular character, with [[Ed Solomon]] writing the screenplay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/johnny-depp-invisible-man-movie-universal-1201699474/|title=Johnny Depp To Star In 'The Invisible Man' At Universal|last=Jr|first=Mike Fleming|last2=Jr|first2=Mike Fleming|date=2016-02-10|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> The film was set to be part of [[Universal Pictures]]' modern-day [[Reboot (fiction)|reboot]] of their [[Universal Monsters]], called [[Dark Universe (franchise)|Dark Universe]]. The would-be series of films was set to begin with ''[[The Mummy (2017 film)|The Mummy]]'' and followed by a remake of ''Bride of Frankenstein'' in 2019. In 2017, ''The Mummy'' director [[Alex Kurtzman]] stated that fans should expect at least one film per year in the shared film universe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/06/06/monster-movie-fans-can-expect-one-film-a-year-from-the-brand-new-dark-universe-6684959/|title=Alex Kurtzman says monster movie fans should get one Dark Universe film a year|date=6 June 2017|website=metro.co.uk|accessdate=6 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110004829/http://metro.co.uk/2017/06/06/monster-movie-fans-can-expect-one-film-a-year-from-the-brand-new-dark-universe-6684959/|archivedate=10 November 2017}}</ref> However, once ''The Mummy'' was released to negative critical reception and box office returns deemed by the studio as insufficient, changes were made to the Dark Universe to focus on individual storytelling and move away from the shared universe concept.<ref>\n*{{cite magazine|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/alex-kurtzman-chris-morgan-exit-universal-monsterverse-1055854|title=Universal's \"Monsterverse\" in Peril as Top Producers Exit (Exclusive)|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|last2=Couch|first2=Aaron|date=November 8, 2017|accessdate=November 8, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108183009/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/alex-kurtzman-chris-morgan-exit-universal-monsterverse-1055854|archivedate=November 8, 2017}}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/alex-kurtzman-chris-morgan-exit-universal-monsterverse-1055854|title=Universal's 'Monsterverse' in Peril as Top Producers Exit (Exclusive)|date=November 8, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]]}}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/uk/movies/the-mummy/53302/dark-universe-the-undignified-death-of-a-cinematic-universe|title=Dark Universe: the undignified death of a cinematic universe|work=Den of Geek|access-date=November 15, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Universal announced that all future movies on their horror characters would focus on standalone stories, avoiding inter-connectivity.<ref>[https://variety.com/2019/film/news/universal-finds-director-invisible-man-studios-monster-legacy-1203117708/ \u2018Invisible Man\u2019 Finds Director, Sets New Course for Universal\u2019s Monster Legacy (EXCLUSIVE)]</ref> Successful horror film producer [[Jason Blum]], founder of production company [[Blumhouse Productions]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/blumhouse-prods-signs-10-year-production-deal-with-universal-pictures/|title=Blumhouse Signs 10-Year Production Deal With Universal Pictures|last=Cunningham|first=Todd|date=July 20, 2014|website=[[The Wrap]]|accessdate=September 11, 2016}}</ref> had at various times publicly expressed his interest in reviving and working on future installments within the Dark Universe films. ''The Invisible Man'' was set to be written and directed by [[Leigh Whannell]], and produced by Blum, but would not star Depp as previously reported.<ref>\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/jason-blum-dark-universe-interest/|title=Spawn Producer Jason Blum Interested In Reviving Dark Universe|date=18 August 2018|publisher=}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/universal-finds-director-invisible-man-studios-monster-legacy-1203117708/|title='Invisible Man' Finds Director, Sets New Course for Universal's Monster Legacy (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|last2=Kroll|first2=Justin|date=2019-01-25|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\nOn February 22, 2020, during an interview with Cinemablend's ReelBlend Podcast, Whannell stated that the film was never planned to be part of any cinematic universe, including the Dark Universe.<ref name=\"CinemaBlend\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2490675/the-invisible-man-was-never-considered-a-part-of-the-dark-universe-leigh-whannell-reveals|title=The Invisible Man Was Never Considered A Part Of The Dark Universe, Leigh Whannell Reveals|website= Cinemablend|date=February 22, 2020|first=Sarah El|last=Mahmoud}}</ref> He stated, {{quote|\"It was weird, this film came about in a really random way. It wasn't like I was plugged into some kind of worldbuilding. I had just finished ''[[Upgrade (film)|Upgrade]]'', they called me in for a meeting with some of these Universal and Blumhouse execs\u2026 I go to this meeting, and they didn't really talk about ''Upgrade''. I mean, they said they liked it and they moved on. So, I'm sitting on this couch thinking, 'What am I here for? What is this meeting about?' And they started talking about ''The Invisible Man''.\"<ref name=\"CinemaBlend\" />}}\n\n===Casting===\nIn March 2019, [[Elisabeth Moss]] entered early negotiations to star,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/universal-elisabeth-moss-invisible-man-1203153172/|title=Elisabeth Moss Circling Universal's 'Invisible Man' (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|last2=Kroll|first2=Justin|date=2019-03-01|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> with her official casting the following month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/elisabeth-moss-the-invisible-man-casting-1202594633/|title=Elisabeth Moss Officially Boards Universal-Blumhouse's 'The Invisible Man'|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2019-04-12|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> [[Storm Reid]], [[Aldis Hodge]], and [[Harriet Dyer]] later joined the cast,<ref>\n*{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/the-invisible-man-blumhouse-universal-storm-reid-joins-cast-1202611915/|title=Universal-Blumhouse's 'The Invisible Man' Adds 'A Wrinkle In Time' Star Storm Reid|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2019-05-10|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/blumhouse-invisible-man-casts-aldis-hodge-straight-outta-compton-1202634959/|title=Blumhouse & Universal's 'The Invisible Man' Adds 'Straight Outta Compton' & 'Clemency' Actor Aldis Hodge|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2019-06-19|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/the-inbetween-harriet-dyer-joins-blumhouse-universals-the-invisible-man-1202635875/|title=Harriet Dyer, Star Of NBC's 'The InBetween', Joins Blumhouse-Universal's 'The Invisible Man'|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2019-06-20|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> with [[Oliver Jackson-Cohen]] set to play the titular role in July.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/blumhouse-universal-find-their-invisible-man-in-oliver-jackson-cohen-1202645510/|title=Blumhouse & Universal Find Their 'Invisible Man' In Oliver Jackson-Cohen|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2019-07-12|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nPrincipal photography began on July 16, 2019 and ended on September 17, 2019 in Sydney, Australia.<ref>\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/1083445-production-begins-on-new-the-invisible-man|title=Production Begins on New The Invisible Man|last=Perry|first=Spencer|date=2019-07-16|website=Comingsoon|language=en|access-date=2019-07-16}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/LWhannell/status/1173692175055388672?s=09|title=Blumhouse's 'The Invisible Man' Wraps Production|last=Whannell|first=Leigh|date=2019-09-17|website=[[Twitter]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n[[Benjamin Wallfisch]] composed the music for the film.<ref>{{cite web |title=Benjamin Wallfisch Scoring Leigh Whannell's 'The Invisible Man' {{!}} Film Music Reporter |url=https://filmmusicreporter.com/2020/01/28/benjamin-wallfisch-scoring-leigh-whannells-the-invisible-man/ |website=Film Music Reporter |date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> Back Lot Music has released the soundtrack.\n\n==Release==\n''The Invisible Man'' was theatrically released in the United States on February 28, 2020 by [[Universal Pictures]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/the-invisible-man-release-date-elisabeth-moss-universal-monster-movie-1202619289/|title=Blumhouse's 'The Invisible Man' Will Emerge Two Weeks Earlier \u2013 Update|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|date=August 22, 2019|accessdate=August 22, 2019}}</ref> It was originally scheduled for release on March 13, 2020, but in August 2019 was moved up two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/blumhouses-the-invisible-man-sets-march-2020-release-date/|title=Blumhouse's 'The Invisible Man' Sets March 2020 Release Date|website=[[The Wrap]]|first=Beatrice|last=Verhoeven|date=May 20, 2019|accessdate=August 20, 2019}}</ref> On March 20, it was one of many films prematurely released to streaming platforms for rent in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"streaming\">{{Cite web |url=https://slate.com/culture/2020/03/coronavirus-universal-movies-trolls-2-the-hunt-invisible-man-streaming.html |last=Adams |first=Sam |title=Universal Reacts to Coronavirus by Releasing New Movies Straight to Streaming |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n{{As of|2020|3|25|df=US}}, ''The Invisible Man'' has grossed $64.9&nbsp;million in the United States and Canada, and $59.6&nbsp;million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $124.5&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"NUM\"/><ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was projected to gross $24\u201330&nbsp;million from 3,610 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref name=WrapProj>{{Cite web|url= https://www.thewrap.com/invisible-man-box-office-hit-no-one-sees-coming-elisabeth-moss/ |title= Will 'The Invisible Man' Become a Box Office Hit No One Sees Coming? |website=[[TheWrap]]|author=Jeremy Fuster|accessdate=February 25, 2020|date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> It made $9.8&nbsp;million on its first day, including $1.65&nbsp;million from Thursday night previews. The film went on to debut to $28.9&nbsp;million, topping the box office.<ref name=opening>{{Cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2020/02/the-invisible-man-opening-weekend-box-office-blumhouse-elisabeth-moss-1202870555/ |title= 'The Invisible Man' Sighting At B.O. Swells To $29M \u2013 Sunday AM Update |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=March 1, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> The film made $15.1&nbsp;million in its second weekend (dropping 46%, above-average for a horror film) and then $5.9&nbsp;million in its third weekend.<ref>\n*{{Cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2020/03/onward-opening-weekend-disney-pixar-coronavirus-invisible-man-1202876016/ |title= \u2018Onward\u2019 Seeing Blas\u00e9 $40M Domestic Opening, $68M WW: Are Coronavirus Fears Impacting B.O.? \u2013 Sunday Update |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=March 8, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=March 8, 2020}}\n*{{Cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2020/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-i-still-believe-the-hunt-weekend-box-office-coronavirus-1202882333/ |title= Weekend Box Office Headed To 22-Year-Low At $58M+ As Coronavirus Fears Grip Nation |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|accessdate=March 15, 2020|date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> In the film's fourth weekend, due to the mass theater closures around the country, it made $64,000 from 111 locations, mostly [[drive-in theater|drive-ins]].<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2020/03/coronavirus-drive-in-movie-theaters-exhibition-shutdown-onward-1202890329/ |title=Drive-Ins Continue To Post Best Ticket Sales In Weekend Box Office Wiped Out By Theater Closures |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=March 23, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=March 24, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n[[Review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported that 91% of 345 reviews of the film were positive, with an average rating of 7.69/10. The website's critics consensus reads: \"Smart, well-acted, and above all scary, ''The Invisible Man'' proves that sometimes, the classic source material for a fresh reboot can be hiding in plain sight.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_invisible_man_2020 |title=The Invisible Man (2020) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] calculated a weighted average score of 71 out of 100 based on 57 critic reviews, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-invisible-man |title=The Invisible Man Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B+\" on an A+ to F scale, and [[PostTrak]] reported it received an overall positive score of 76% and an average four out of five stars, with 53% of people they polled saying they would definitely recommend the film.<ref name=opening/>\n\n[[Manohla Dargis]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that Moss's performance \"gives the movie its emotional stakes,\" adding, \"while her agony can be unnerving, it is even more shivery when her weeping stops and this horror-movie damsel in distress becomes a threat.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/movies/the-invisible-man-review.html|title='The Invisible Man' Review: Gaslight Nation, Domestic Edition|last=Dargis|first=Manohla|date=February 26, 2020|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> Writing for ''[[The A. V. Club]]'', Jesse Hassenger gave the film a \"B+\", also praising Moss's performance and the film's centering of her character's experience;<ref name=\"avc\">{{cite web|url=https://film.avclub.com/a-new-version-of-the-invisible-man-makes-one-of-his-vic-1841840293|title=A New Version of ''The Invisible Man'' Makes One of His Victims Intensely Visible|last=Hassenger|first=Jesse|date=February 25, 2020|publisher=[[The A. V. Club]]|accessdate=February 25, 2020}}</ref> the publication followed up with a video review from senior writer Katie Rife and [[Ignatiy Vishnevetsky]], who also gave a positive review, for the aesthetic and filmmaking of [[Blumhouse Productions]] and Moss's performance.<ref name=\"avcv\">{{Cite web |last2=Vishnevetsky |first2=Ignatiy |first1=Katie |last1=Katie |url=https://film.avclub.com/elisabeth-moss-is-visibly-great-in-blumhouse-s-new-take-1841961623 |title=Elisabeth Moss is Visibly Great in Blumhouse's New Take on ''The Invisible Man'' |date=February 28, 2020 |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Alison Willmore of ''[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]'' commented about the effectiveness of Moss's facial expressions, and said that she \"has established herself as an empress of the onscreen breakdown, our lady of ruined eye makeup\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/02/the-invisible-man-movie-review.html|title=Elisabeth Moss Makes The Invisible Man Worth Seeing|last=Willmore|first=Alison|date=February 26, 2020|website=Vulture|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Patrick Cavanaugh of ComicBook.com gave the film four out of five stars, and wrote that Whannell's film is \"an experience that is both effective as a full-blown horror film and as a chilling reminder of the abuse one can suffer from a supposed loved one.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://comicbook.com/horror/2020/02/25/invisible-man-review-reboot-elisabeth-moss-universal-monsters-leigh-whannell/ |title=The Invisible Man Review: A Real-Life Movie Monster Breathes Life Into an Antiquated Concept |last=Cavanaugh |first=Patrick |website=Comicbook.com |date=February 25, 2020 |access-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> \n\nConversely, Nicholas Barber from [[BBC]] gave the film two out of five stars, opining that \"the latest remake of the HG Wells tale offers a timely feminist spin \u2013 but it's lacking in thrills.\" He criticized the film's vagueness, concluding, \"at a time when small-scale horror movies can be as stunning as ''[[A Quiet Place (film)|A Quiet Place]]'' and ''[[Get Out]]'', a film as perfunctory as ''The Invisible Man'' feels insulting.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20200226-invisible-man-film-review-two-stars|title=Invisible Man film review: 'Nothing to see here'|last=Barber|first=Nicholas|date=26 February 2020|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Franchise future==\nIn November 2019, it was announced that a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] film centered around the [[The Invisible Woman (1940 film)|female counterpart]] to [[Griffin (The Invisible Man)|Invisible Man]] was in development. [[Elizabeth Banks]] was set to star in, direct, and produce a new adaptation of ''[[The Invisible Woman (1940 film)|The Invisible Woman]]'' (1940), based on her own original story pitch. [[Erin Cressida Wilson]] will write the script for the reboot of the female monster, while [[Max Handelman]] and Alison Small will serve as producer and executive producer, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kroll|first=Justin|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/elizabeth-banks-invisible-woman-universal-1203417107/|title=Elizabeth Banks to Direct, Star in ''Invisible Woman'' for Universal|date=November 26, 2019|website=Variety|accessdate=November 26, 2019}}</ref> Banks was allowed to choose a project by [[Universal Pictures]] from the roster of [[Universal Monsters]], ultimately choosing ''The Invisible Woman''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/bride-of-frankenstein-universal-amy-pascal-angelina-jolie-1203500987/|title=Hollywood Still Trying to Put a Ring on Universal\u2019s \u2018Bride of Frankenstein\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Donnelly|first=Matt|last2=Donnelly|first2=Matt|date=2020-02-11|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official}}\n* {{IMDb title|1051906}}\n\n{{The Invisible Man}}\n{{Leigh Whannell}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Invisible Man, The}}\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:2020 horror films]]\n[[Category:2020s horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:2020s science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:2020s science fiction thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction thriller films]]\n[[Category:Australian films]]\n[[Category:Australian horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:Australian science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:Australian science fiction thriller films]]\n[[Category:Blumhouse Productions films]]\n[[Category:Films about domestic violence]]\n[[Category:Films about invisibility]]\n[[Category:Films about mass murder]]\n[[Category:Films about psychopaths]]\n[[Category:Films based on The Invisible Man]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Leigh Whannell]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Jason Blum]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Benjamin Wallfisch]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2020]]\n[[Category:Films set in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Leigh Whannell]]\n[[Category:Universal Classic Monsters films]]\n[[Category:Universal Monsters]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{short description|2020 film directed by Leigh Whannell}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Invisible Man\n| image          = File:The Invisible Man (2020 film) - release poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Leigh Whannell]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jason Blum]]\n* Kylie du Fresne\n}}\n| writer         = Leigh Whannell\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[The Invisible Man]]''|[[H. G. Wells]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Elisabeth Moss]]\n* [[Aldis Hodge]]\n* [[Storm Reid]]\n* [[Harriet Dyer]]\n* [[Michael Dorman]]\n* [[Oliver Jackson-Cohen]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Benjamin Wallfisch]]\n| cinematography = Stefan Duscio\n| editing        = Andy Canny\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Universal Pictures]]\n* [[Blumhouse Productions]]\n* Nervous Tick\n* [[Goalpost Pictures]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|2|27|Australia|2020|2|28|United States}}\n| runtime        = 124 minutes\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n* Australia\n}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $7 million<ref name=BOM/>\n| gross          = $125.8 million<ref name=NUM>{{cite web |url= https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Invisible-Man-The-(2020)#tab=summary |title=The Invisible Man (2020)|website= [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate= March 20, 2020 }}</ref><ref name=BOM>{{cite web |url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt1051906/?ref_=bo_se_r_1 |title=The Invisible Man (2020)|website= [[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate= March 26, 2020 }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Invisible Man''''' is a 2020 [[Science fiction film|science fiction]] [[horror]] [[thriller film]] written and directed by [[Leigh Whannell]]. It follows a woman who believes she is being stalked by her abusive and wealthy boyfriend even after his apparent suicide.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://celebrityinsider.org/invisible-man-pulls-in-a-solid-box-office-weekend-373793/ |title=Invisible Man Pulls In A Solid Box Office Weekend |last=Bridget |first=Hill |date=29 February 2020 |website=celebrityinsider.org |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> She ultimately deduces that he has acquired the ability to become invisible.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2020/02/review-invisible-man-leigh-whannell-elisabeth-moss/607153/ |title=This Time, The Invisible Man Is Really About a Woman |last=David |first=Sims |date=27 February 2020 |website=theatlantic.com |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> The film stars [[Elisabeth Moss]], [[Aldis Hodge]], [[Storm Reid]], [[Harriet Dyer]], [[Michael Dorman]], and [[Oliver Jackson-Cohen]]. It is an international co-production of the United States and Australia.\n\nThe development of a new [[Invisible Man (film series)|''Invisible Man'']] film began as early as 2006. The project was revived as part of Universal's shared cinematic universe in 2016, intended to consist of their classic monsters, with [[Johnny Depp]] attached to star in the title role. After ''[[The Mummy (2017 film)|The Mummy]]'' was released in 2017 to critical and financial failure, development was halted on all projects. In early 2019, the studio changed their plans from a serialized universe to films based on individualized story-telling and the project reentered development. [[Principal photography]] lasted from July to September 2019 in [[Sydney]], Australia.\n\n''The Invisible Man'' was theatrically released in the United States on February 28, 2020, by [[Universal Pictures]]. The film received positive reviews from critics, with praise for Moss' performance, its inventive modernization of the [[The Invisible Man|novel's]] plot, and the combination of scares with \"a smart narrative about how women can be manipulated and abused in harmful relationships\".<ref name=WrapProj/> The film also became a commercial success, grossing $125.8&nbsp;million worldwide against a $7&nbsp;million budget and it is currently the [[2020 in film|fifth highest-grossing film of 2020]]. However, due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] closing theaters across the globe, Universal announced the film would be made available for [[Video on demand|digital rental]] just three weeks after it was released theatrically.\n\n== Plot ==\nTrapped in a violent, controlling relationship with wealthy optics engineer and businessman [[Griffin (The Invisible Man)|Adrian Griffin]] ([[Oliver Jackson-Cohen]]), Cecilia Kass ([[Elisabeth Moss]])\u00a0drugs him with [[Diazepam]] and escapes their home into the nearby woods to wait for her sister, Emily ([[Harriet Dyer]]). After she arrives, Adrian nearly catches Cecilia, but the pair are able to escape.\n\nCecilia hides out with childhood friend, Detective James Lanier ([[Aldis Hodge]]), and his teenage daughter Sydney ([[Storm Reid]]). Two weeks later, Adrian seemingly commits [[suicide]] and leaves Cecilia $5 million in his will handled and organized by his lawyer brother, Tom ([[Michael Dorman]]). As Cecilia tries to move forward, she is plagued by several unexplained experiences. During a job interview, she faints after finding her portfolio's contents removed and is taken to the hospital. Later, the doctor calls and says they found high levels of Diazepam in her system. Shortly after returning home, Cecilia finds the same bottle she drugged Adrian with, which she dropped during her escape, in her bathroom.\n\nShe arranges a meeting with Tom\u00a0and James, insisting that Adrian faked his death and used his optics expertise to become invisible in order to torment her, but gets rebuffed. Cecilia turns to her sister, but Emily refuses to acknowledge her after receiving an email from Cecilia's account stating she never wants to see her again. Later, she is comforted by Sydney, but Sydney is hit by an unseen force, leading her and James to assume Cecilia did it. While a furious James rushes his daughter out of the house, Cecilia tries a number of tactics to catch the figure. After finding Adrian's old phone in the attic and covering the figure with paint, she ends up in a violent struggle before escaping to Adrian's home to investigate. In his lab, she finds a suit that confirms her suspicions. After hiding it in a closet, the invisible figure attacks again, so Cecilia flees and contacts Emily. The pair meet in a restaurant, though as Cecilia begins to tell her what she found, the invisible figure slits Emily's throat with a knife and places it in Cecilia's hand, framing her for the crime.\n\nRemanded to a [[mental hospital]] while she awaits trial, the staff informs Cecilia that she is pregnant. Tom visits her and offers to get her charges dropped if she agrees to \"return to him\" and raise the child, implying that he helped his brother stage his suicide while revealing Adrian tampered with her [[birth control]] to ensure she became pregnant. Cecilia refuses to take the deal and steals a pen from his briefcase. That night, she uses the pen to pretend to commit suicide to draw the invisible figure out. When the figure tries to stop her, she stabs him repeatedly, causing the suit to malfunction. The security team arrives, but the invisible figure violently incapacitates them before fleeing the hospital, with Cecilia in pursuit. Promising not to harm her because of her pregnancy, the figure instead threatens to attack those she loves.\n\nCecilia races to James' house, where she finds the invisible figure attacking him and Sydney. She manages to shoot the figure after spraying him with a fire extinguisher, but when she unmasks him, she finds Tom in the suit. Police find a captive Adrian alive at his house, tied up in his basement and claiming Tom held him prisoner. Cecilia quickly disputes this, insisting the brothers must have shared the suit, with Adrian sending Tom to the house knowing what would happen.\n\nIn an attempt to get Adrian to confess, she meets him at his house to discuss her pregnancy while James listens in on a wire. She agrees to mend their relationship, but only if he confesses to being the invisible figure. Adrian insists Tom did kidnap him, claiming that the experience changed his outlook on life and how he treated her in their relationship. When she begins to cry, Adrian alludes to former abuse using similar phrasing to that of the invisible figure. Smiling, Cecilia departs to use the restroom. Moments later, the room's security camera captures Adrian seemingly committing suicide. Cecilia returns and, apparently distraught, calls the police. Out of the camera's sight however, she silently taunts Adrian; having retrieved the spare suit she hid earlier to kill him.\n\nWhen James arrives and asks what happened, she confirms what the camera saw. He spots the suit in her bag, but accepts her story and allows her to leave. Relieved that she's finally free from Adrian, Cecilia leaves the house with the suit.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Elisabeth Moss]] as Cecilia \"Cee\" Kass\n* [[Oliver Jackson-Cohen]] as [[Griffin (The Invisible Man)|Adrian Griffin]]\n* [[Aldis Hodge]] as James Lanier, a San Francisco police detective, Sydney's father and Cee\u2019s childhood friend\n* [[Storm Reid]] as Sydney Lanier, James' teenage daughter\n* [[Harriet Dyer]] as Emily Kass, Cee\u2019s sister\n* [[Michael Dorman]] as [[Griffin (The Invisible Man)|Tom Griffin]], Adrian's brother and lawyer\n* Benedict Hardie as Marc\n* Amali Golden as Annie\n* Sam Smith as Detective Reckley\n* [[Nash Edgerton]] as a Security Guard\n* Zara Michaels as a Nurse\n* Vivienne Greer as Screaming Woman\n* [[Anthony Brandon Wong]] as Accident Victim\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nDevelopment of a new ''The Invisible Man'' film began as early as 2006 when [[David S. Goyer]] was hired to write the screenplay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstshowing.net/2008/david-s-goyer-directing-the-invisible-man-before-magneto/|title=David S. Goyer Directing The Invisible Man Before Magneto|last=Billington|first=Alex|date=December 12, 2008|website=FirstShowing.net|language=en-US|accessdate=July 15, 2019}}</ref> Goyer remained attached to the project as late as 2011, with little to no further development on the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/david-goyer-invisible-man-remake/|title=David S. Goyer's 'Invisible Man' Remake Is Still Alive|website=screenrant.com|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, the project was announced to be revived as part of Universal's [[cinematic universe]], intended to consist of their [[Universal Classic Monsters|classic monsters]]. [[Johnny Depp]] was cast as the titular character, with [[Ed Solomon]] writing the screenplay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/johnny-depp-invisible-man-movie-universal-1201699474/|title=Johnny Depp To Star In 'The Invisible Man' At Universal|last=Jr|first=Mike Fleming|last2=Jr|first2=Mike Fleming|date=2016-02-10|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> The film was set to be part of [[Universal Pictures]]' modern-day [[Reboot (fiction)|reboot]] of their [[Universal Monsters]], called [[Dark Universe (franchise)|Dark Universe]]. The would-be series of films was set to begin with ''[[The Mummy (2017 film)|The Mummy]]'' and followed by a remake of ''Bride of Frankenstein'' in 2019. In 2017, ''The Mummy'' director [[Alex Kurtzman]] stated that fans should expect at least one film per year in the shared film universe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/06/06/monster-movie-fans-can-expect-one-film-a-year-from-the-brand-new-dark-universe-6684959/|title=Alex Kurtzman says monster movie fans should get one Dark Universe film a year|date=6 June 2017|website=metro.co.uk|accessdate=6 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110004829/http://metro.co.uk/2017/06/06/monster-movie-fans-can-expect-one-film-a-year-from-the-brand-new-dark-universe-6684959/|archivedate=10 November 2017}}</ref> However, once ''The Mummy'' was released to negative critical reception and box office returns deemed by the studio as insufficient, changes were made to the Dark Universe to focus on individual storytelling and move away from the shared universe concept.<ref>\n*{{cite magazine|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/alex-kurtzman-chris-morgan-exit-universal-monsterverse-1055854|title=Universal's \"Monsterverse\" in Peril as Top Producers Exit (Exclusive)|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|last2=Couch|first2=Aaron|date=November 8, 2017|accessdate=November 8, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108183009/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/alex-kurtzman-chris-morgan-exit-universal-monsterverse-1055854|archivedate=November 8, 2017}}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/alex-kurtzman-chris-morgan-exit-universal-monsterverse-1055854|title=Universal's 'Monsterverse' in Peril as Top Producers Exit (Exclusive)|date=November 8, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]]}}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/uk/movies/the-mummy/53302/dark-universe-the-undignified-death-of-a-cinematic-universe|title=Dark Universe: the undignified death of a cinematic universe|work=Den of Geek|access-date=November 15, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Universal announced that all future movies on their horror characters would focus on standalone stories, avoiding inter-connectivity.<ref>[https://variety.com/2019/film/news/universal-finds-director-invisible-man-studios-monster-legacy-1203117708/ \u2018Invisible Man\u2019 Finds Director, Sets New Course for Universal\u2019s Monster Legacy (EXCLUSIVE)]</ref> Successful horror film producer [[Jason Blum]], founder of production company [[Blumhouse Productions]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/blumhouse-prods-signs-10-year-production-deal-with-universal-pictures/|title=Blumhouse Signs 10-Year Production Deal With Universal Pictures|last=Cunningham|first=Todd|date=July 20, 2014|website=[[The Wrap]]|accessdate=September 11, 2016}}</ref> had at various times publicly expressed his interest in reviving and working on future installments within the Dark Universe films. ''The Invisible Man'' was set to be written and directed by [[Leigh Whannell]], and produced by Blum, but would not star Depp as previously reported.<ref>\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/jason-blum-dark-universe-interest/|title=Spawn Producer Jason Blum Interested In Reviving Dark Universe|date=18 August 2018|publisher=}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/universal-finds-director-invisible-man-studios-monster-legacy-1203117708/|title='Invisible Man' Finds Director, Sets New Course for Universal's Monster Legacy (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|last2=Kroll|first2=Justin|date=2019-01-25|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\nOn February 22, 2020, during an interview with Cinemablend's ReelBlend Podcast, Whannell stated that the film was never planned to be part of any cinematic universe, including the Dark Universe.<ref name=\"CinemaBlend\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2490675/the-invisible-man-was-never-considered-a-part-of-the-dark-universe-leigh-whannell-reveals|title=The Invisible Man Was Never Considered A Part Of The Dark Universe, Leigh Whannell Reveals|website= Cinemablend|date=February 22, 2020|first=Sarah El|last=Mahmoud}}</ref> He stated, {{quote|\"It was weird, this film came about in a really random way. It wasn't like I was plugged into some kind of worldbuilding. I had just finished ''[[Upgrade (film)|Upgrade]]'', they called me in for a meeting with some of these Universal and Blumhouse execs\u2026 I go to this meeting, and they didn't really talk about ''Upgrade''. I mean, they said they liked it and they moved on. So, I'm sitting on this couch thinking, 'What am I here for? What is this meeting about?' And they started talking about ''The Invisible Man''.\"<ref name=\"CinemaBlend\" />}}\n\n===Casting===\nIn March 2019, [[Elisabeth Moss]] entered early negotiations to star,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/universal-elisabeth-moss-invisible-man-1203153172/|title=Elisabeth Moss Circling Universal's 'Invisible Man' (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|last2=Kroll|first2=Justin|date=2019-03-01|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> with her official casting the following month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/elisabeth-moss-the-invisible-man-casting-1202594633/|title=Elisabeth Moss Officially Boards Universal-Blumhouse's 'The Invisible Man'|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2019-04-12|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> [[Storm Reid]], [[Aldis Hodge]], and [[Harriet Dyer]] later joined the cast,<ref>\n*{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/the-invisible-man-blumhouse-universal-storm-reid-joins-cast-1202611915/|title=Universal-Blumhouse's 'The Invisible Man' Adds 'A Wrinkle In Time' Star Storm Reid|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2019-05-10|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/blumhouse-invisible-man-casts-aldis-hodge-straight-outta-compton-1202634959/|title=Blumhouse & Universal's 'The Invisible Man' Adds 'Straight Outta Compton' & 'Clemency' Actor Aldis Hodge|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2019-06-19|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/the-inbetween-harriet-dyer-joins-blumhouse-universals-the-invisible-man-1202635875/|title=Harriet Dyer, Star Of NBC's 'The InBetween', Joins Blumhouse-Universal's 'The Invisible Man'|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2019-06-20|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> with [[Oliver Jackson-Cohen]] set to play the titular role in July.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/blumhouse-universal-find-their-invisible-man-in-oliver-jackson-cohen-1202645510/|title=Blumhouse & Universal Find Their 'Invisible Man' In Oliver Jackson-Cohen|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2019-07-12|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nPrincipal photography began on July 16, 2019 and ended on September 17, 2019 in Sydney, Australia.<ref>\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/1083445-production-begins-on-new-the-invisible-man|title=Production Begins on New The Invisible Man|last=Perry|first=Spencer|date=2019-07-16|website=Comingsoon|language=en|access-date=2019-07-16}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/LWhannell/status/1173692175055388672?s=09|title=Blumhouse's 'The Invisible Man' Wraps Production|last=Whannell|first=Leigh|date=2019-09-17|website=[[Twitter]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n[[Benjamin Wallfisch]] composed the music for the film.<ref>{{cite web |title=Benjamin Wallfisch Scoring Leigh Whannell's 'The Invisible Man' {{!}} Film Music Reporter |url=https://filmmusicreporter.com/2020/01/28/benjamin-wallfisch-scoring-leigh-whannells-the-invisible-man/ |website=Film Music Reporter |date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> Back Lot Music has released the soundtrack.\n\n==Release==\n''The Invisible Man'' was theatrically released in the United States on February 28, 2020 by [[Universal Pictures]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/the-invisible-man-release-date-elisabeth-moss-universal-monster-movie-1202619289/|title=Blumhouse's 'The Invisible Man' Will Emerge Two Weeks Earlier \u2013 Update|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|date=August 22, 2019|accessdate=August 22, 2019}}</ref> It was originally scheduled for release on March 13, 2020, but in August 2019 was moved up two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/blumhouses-the-invisible-man-sets-march-2020-release-date/|title=Blumhouse's 'The Invisible Man' Sets March 2020 Release Date|website=[[The Wrap]]|first=Beatrice|last=Verhoeven|date=May 20, 2019|accessdate=August 20, 2019}}</ref> On March 20, it was one of many films prematurely released to streaming platforms for rent in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"streaming\">{{Cite web |url=https://slate.com/culture/2020/03/coronavirus-universal-movies-trolls-2-the-hunt-invisible-man-streaming.html |last=Adams |first=Sam |title=Universal Reacts to Coronavirus by Releasing New Movies Straight to Streaming |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n{{As of|2020|3|25|df=US}}, ''The Invisible Man'' has grossed $64.9&nbsp;million in the United States and Canada, and $59.6&nbsp;million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $124.5&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"NUM\"/><ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was projected to gross $24\u201330&nbsp;million from 3,610 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref name=WrapProj>{{Cite web|url= https://www.thewrap.com/invisible-man-box-office-hit-no-one-sees-coming-elisabeth-moss/ |title= Will 'The Invisible Man' Become a Box Office Hit No One Sees Coming? |website=[[TheWrap]]|author=Jeremy Fuster|accessdate=February 25, 2020|date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> It made $9.8&nbsp;million on its first day, including $1.65&nbsp;million from Thursday night previews. The film went on to debut to $28.9&nbsp;million, topping the box office.<ref name=opening>{{Cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2020/02/the-invisible-man-opening-weekend-box-office-blumhouse-elisabeth-moss-1202870555/ |title= 'The Invisible Man' Sighting At B.O. Swells To $29M \u2013 Sunday AM Update |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=March 1, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> The film made $15.1&nbsp;million in its second weekend (dropping 46%, above-average for a horror film) and then $5.9&nbsp;million in its third weekend.<ref>\n*{{Cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2020/03/onward-opening-weekend-disney-pixar-coronavirus-invisible-man-1202876016/ |title= \u2018Onward\u2019 Seeing Blas\u00e9 $40M Domestic Opening, $68M WW: Are Coronavirus Fears Impacting B.O.? \u2013 Sunday Update |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=March 8, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=March 8, 2020}}\n*{{Cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2020/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-i-still-believe-the-hunt-weekend-box-office-coronavirus-1202882333/ |title= Weekend Box Office Headed To 22-Year-Low At $58M+ As Coronavirus Fears Grip Nation |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|accessdate=March 15, 2020|date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> In the film's fourth weekend, due to the mass theater closures around the country, it made $64,000 from 111 locations, mostly [[drive-in theater|drive-ins]].<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2020/03/coronavirus-drive-in-movie-theaters-exhibition-shutdown-onward-1202890329/ |title=Drive-Ins Continue To Post Best Ticket Sales In Weekend Box Office Wiped Out By Theater Closures |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=March 23, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=March 24, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n[[Review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported that 91% of 345 reviews of the film were positive, with an average rating of 7.69/10. The website's critics consensus reads: \"Smart, well-acted, and above all scary, ''The Invisible Man'' proves that sometimes, the classic source material for a fresh reboot can be hiding in plain sight.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_invisible_man_2020 |title=The Invisible Man (2020) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] calculated a weighted average score of 71 out of 100 based on 57 critic reviews, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-invisible-man |title=The Invisible Man Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B+\" on an A+ to F scale, and [[PostTrak]] reported it received an overall positive score of 76% and an average four out of five stars, with 53% of people they polled saying they would definitely recommend the film.<ref name=opening/>\n\n[[Manohla Dargis]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that Moss's performance \"gives the movie its emotional stakes,\" adding, \"while her agony can be unnerving, it is even more shivery when her weeping stops and this horror-movie damsel in distress becomes a threat.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/movies/the-invisible-man-review.html|title='The Invisible Man' Review: Gaslight Nation, Domestic Edition|last=Dargis|first=Manohla|date=February 26, 2020|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> Writing for ''[[The A. V. Club]]'', Jesse Hassenger gave the film a \"B+\", also praising Moss's performance and the film's centering of her character's experience;<ref name=\"avc\">{{cite web|url=https://film.avclub.com/a-new-version-of-the-invisible-man-makes-one-of-his-vic-1841840293|title=A New Version of ''The Invisible Man'' Makes One of His Victims Intensely Visible|last=Hassenger|first=Jesse|date=February 25, 2020|publisher=[[The A. V. Club]]|accessdate=February 25, 2020}}</ref> the publication followed up with a video review from senior writer Katie Rife and [[Ignatiy Vishnevetsky]], who also gave a positive review, for the aesthetic and filmmaking of [[Blumhouse Productions]] and Moss's performance.<ref name=\"avcv\">{{Cite web |last2=Vishnevetsky |first2=Ignatiy |first1=Katie |last1=Katie |url=https://film.avclub.com/elisabeth-moss-is-visibly-great-in-blumhouse-s-new-take-1841961623 |title=Elisabeth Moss is Visibly Great in Blumhouse's New Take on ''The Invisible Man'' |date=February 28, 2020 |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Alison Willmore of ''[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]'' commented about the effectiveness of Moss's facial expressions, and said that she \"has established herself as an empress of the onscreen breakdown, our lady of ruined eye makeup\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/02/the-invisible-man-movie-review.html|title=Elisabeth Moss Makes The Invisible Man Worth Seeing|last=Willmore|first=Alison|date=February 26, 2020|website=Vulture|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Patrick Cavanaugh of ComicBook.com gave the film four out of five stars, and wrote that Whannell's film is \"an experience that is both effective as a full-blown horror film and as a chilling reminder of the abuse one can suffer from a supposed loved one.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://comicbook.com/horror/2020/02/25/invisible-man-review-reboot-elisabeth-moss-universal-monsters-leigh-whannell/ |title=The Invisible Man Review: A Real-Life Movie Monster Breathes Life Into an Antiquated Concept |last=Cavanaugh |first=Patrick |website=Comicbook.com |date=February 25, 2020 |access-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> \n\nConversely, Nicholas Barber from [[BBC]] gave the film two out of five stars, opining that \"the latest remake of the HG Wells tale offers a timely feminist spin \u2013 but it's lacking in thrills.\" He criticized the film's vagueness, concluding, \"at a time when small-scale horror movies can be as stunning as ''[[A Quiet Place (film)|A Quiet Place]]'' and ''[[Get Out]]'', a film as perfunctory as ''The Invisible Man'' feels insulting.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20200226-invisible-man-film-review-two-stars|title=Invisible Man film review: 'Nothing to see here'|last=Barber|first=Nicholas|date=26 February 2020|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Franchise future==\nIn November 2019, it was announced that a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] film centered around the [[The Invisible Woman (1940 film)|female counterpart]] to [[Griffin (The Invisible Man)|Invisible Man]] was in development. [[Elizabeth Banks]] was set to star in, direct, and produce a new adaptation of ''[[The Invisible Woman (1940 film)|The Invisible Woman]]'' (1940), based on her own original story pitch. [[Erin Cressida Wilson]] will write the script for the reboot of the female monster, while [[Max Handelman]] and Alison Small will serve as producer and executive producer, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kroll|first=Justin|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/elizabeth-banks-invisible-woman-universal-1203417107/|title=Elizabeth Banks to Direct, Star in ''Invisible Woman'' for Universal|date=November 26, 2019|website=Variety|accessdate=November 26, 2019}}</ref> Banks was allowed to choose a project by [[Universal Pictures]] from the roster of [[Universal Monsters]], ultimately choosing ''The Invisible Woman''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/bride-of-frankenstein-universal-amy-pascal-angelina-jolie-1203500987/|title=Hollywood Still Trying to Put a Ring on Universal\u2019s \u2018Bride of Frankenstein\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Donnelly|first=Matt|last2=Donnelly|first2=Matt|date=2020-02-11|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official}}\n* {{IMDb title|1051906}}\n\n{{The Invisible Man}}\n{{Leigh Whannell}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Invisible Man, The}}\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:2020 horror films]]\n[[Category:2020s horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:2020s science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:2020s science fiction thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction thriller films]]\n[[Category:Australian films]]\n[[Category:Australian horror thriller films]]\n[[Category:Australian science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:Australian science fiction thriller films]]\n[[Category:Blumhouse Productions films]]\n[[Category:Films about domestic violence]]\n[[Category:Films about invisibility]]\n[[Category:Films about mass murder]]\n[[Category:Films about psychopaths]]\n[[Category:Films based on The Invisible Man]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Leigh Whannell]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Jason Blum]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Benjamin Wallfisch]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2020]]\n[[Category:Films set in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Leigh Whannell]]\n[[Category:Universal Classic Monsters films]]\n[[Category:Universal Monsters]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toHorror(link changed toHorror film) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Invisible_Man_(2020_film)"}
{"title_page": "Sotiris Tsiodras", "text_new": "\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Sotiris Tsiodras\n| birth_name = \n| honorific-prefix = [[Doctor]]\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = \n| caption = \n| imagesize = \n| order1 = \n| office1 = Leader of team charged with the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Greece|Coronavirus pandemic in Greece]] management</br>Government liaison officer on coronavirus pandemic\n| term_start1 = \n| term_end1 = \n| predecessor1 = \n| successor1 =\n| order2 = \n| office2 = \n| term_start2 = \n| term_end2 =\n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2 = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age | 1965 | 10 | 13 | df = y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = \n| awards = \n| spouse = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| profession = Physician and epidemiologist\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Sotiris Tsiodras''' (born 1965) an [[Australia]]-born [[Greek people|Greek]] [[pathologist]] [[physician]], specializing in [[Infectious disease (medical specialty)|infectology]], in charge of [[Greece]]'s management of the [[coronavirus]] [[SARS-CoV-2]] [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Greece|crisis]].\n==Early years and education==\nTsiodras was born on 13 October 1965 in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]], into an [[immigrant]] family originating from [[Argolis|Neohori, Argolis]].<ref name=neohori>{{cite news  |date=22 March 2020 |title='\u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03b5\u03c5\u03c7\u03cc\u03bc\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5 \u03b3\u03b9\u03ac \u03c4\u03bf \u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03af \u03bc\u03b1\u03c2': \u039f\u03b9 \u03b3\u03bf\u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03cd \u03a3\u03c9\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b7 \u03a4\u03c3\u03b9\u03cc\u03b4\u03c1\u03b1 \u03bc\u03b9\u03bb\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd \u03b3\u03b9\u03ac \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03b3\u03b9\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2|url=https://www.arcadiaportal.gr/news/proseyhomaste-gia-paidi-mas-oi-goneis-toy-sotiri-tsiodra-sto-neohori-miloyn-gia-ton-gio-toys|language=Greek|trans-title='We are praying for our child': Sotiris Tsiodras' parents talks about their son|work=Arcadia portal |location= Greece|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> \nAfter the family moved back to Greece, he enrolled into the [[Ioannina]] medical school and then transferred to the [[National and Kapodistrian University of Athens|Athens University]] from which he graduated in March 1991 as a pathologist.<ref name=who>{{cite news  |date=6 April 2020 |title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u03a0\u03bf\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bf \u03bb\u03bf\u03b9\u03bc\u03c9\u03be\u03b9\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c9\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a4\u03c3\u03b9\u03cc\u03b4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03ba\u03ad\u03c1\u03b4\u03b9\u03c3\u03b5 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b5\u03bc\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c3\u03cd\u03bd\u03b7 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ae\u03bd\u03c9\u03bd|url=https://www.iefimerida.gr/ellada/koronoios-poios-einai-o-loimoxiologos-sotiris-tsiodras-poy-kerdise-tin-empistosyni-ton|language=Greek|trans-title=Coronavirus: Who is the Greek infectiologist who has won the trust of Greeks|work=I Efimerida |location=Athens|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n==Medical career==\nTsiodras was appointed at the [https://401gsn.army.gr/ 401 Military Hospital] in 1993 where he served for one year. During the years 1994-1997, he worked as an internal medicine specialist specializing in [[Pathology]] at the [[Einstein Medical Center Philadelphia|Einstein Medical Center Philadelphia]] in the United States. From 1997 to 2001, he enrolled in the programs for [[infectious diseases]] at the [[Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center]] and [[Harvard Medical School]]. Between 1998 and 2001, he worked as a [[research fellow]] at the Harvard Medical School, from which, in June 2001, he received a [[Medical Sciences]] [[Master's Degree|M.A]].<ref name=studies>{{cite news  |date=24 March 2020 |title=Sydney-born immunologist Sotiris Tsiodras, the \u2018voice\u2019 of coronavirus in Greece|url=https://neoskosmos.com/en/161116/sydney-born-immunologist-sotiris-tsiodras-the-voice-of-coronavirus-in-greece/ |work=New World |location= Australia|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, he defended ''[[cum laude]]'' his [[doctoral dissertation]] at the Medical School of the National and Kapodistrian University of Athens.<ref name=dissertation>{{cite web |url=https://www.didaktorika.gr/eadd/handle/10442/13581|title=Effect of protease inhibitors on the metabolic syndrome of patients with HIV infection|last1=Tsiodras |first1=Sotiris |place= |publisher=[[National and Kapodistrian University of Athens]] |date=2003 |doi= 10.12681/eadd/13581|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Virus pandemic in Greece==\nIn 2019, the government appointed a group of experts to co-ordinate the state's management of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Greece|SARS-CoV-2 pandemic]] in Greece.<ref name=team>{{cite news  |date=3 March 2020 |title=\u039f\u03b4\u03b7\u03b3\u03af\u03b5\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03bb\u03bf\u03b9\u03bc\u03c9\u03be\u03b9\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03bf \u03a3\u03c9\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b7 \u03a4\u03c3\u03b9\u03cc\u03b4\u03c1\u03b1 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03b1 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03b5\u03c5\u03c0\u03b1\u03b8\u03ce\u03bd \u03bf\u03bc\u03ac\u03b4\u03c9\u03bd \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03ba\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc|language=Greek|trans-title=Directions from infectiologist Sotiris Tsiodras on the protection of vulnerable groups from the coronavirus|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.gr/entry/odeyies-loimoxiologow-tsiodras-prostasia-efpathon-omadon-koronoio_gr_5e5e4d99c5b67ed38b3885dd |work=[[Huffington Post]] |location=Athens |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> Tsiodras was appointed as the team's leader as well as the government's communications liaison for the health crisis.<ref name=appointment>{{cite news  |date=6 April 2020 |title='Nick Hard' and the soft-spoken professor keeping Greeks virus-safe |url=http://www.rfi.fr/en/wires/20200406-nick-hard-and-soft-spoken-professor-keeping-greeks-virus-safe |work=[[Radio France Internationale]] |location=Paris|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=heroes>{{cite news  |date=5 April 2020|last= Stevis-Gridneff|first= Matina|title=The Rising Heroes of the Coronavirus Era? Nations\u2019 Top Scientists|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/05/world/europe/scientists-coronavirus-heroes.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location= |url-access=subscription|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTsiodras is a practicing [[Eastern Orthodox|Orthodox Christian]], an aficionado of [[Byzantine]] [[hymnology]], and a member of his local-church's choir. He is married to Mina Tsiodras and they have seven children.<ref name=who/>\n==See also==\n*[[Cabinet of Kyriakos Mitsotakis|Greek government, post-2019 elections]]\n*[[Civil_service#Greece|Civil services of Greece]]\n*[[World Health Organisation]]\n*[[SARS]]\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.moh.gov.gr/ Greek Ministry of Health] official website (in [[Greek language|Greek]])\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tsiodras, Sotiris}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Greek people]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Greek descent]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Sotiris Tsiodras\n| birth_name = \n| honorific-prefix = [[Doctor]]\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = \n| caption = \n| imagesize = \n| order1 = \n| office1 = Leader of team charged with the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Greece|Coronavirus pandemic in Greece]] management</br>Government liaison officer on coronavirus pandemic\n| term_start1 = \n| term_end1 = \n| predecessor1 = \n| successor1 =\n| order2 = \n| office2 = \n| term_start2 = \n| term_end2 =\n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2 = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age | 1965 | 10 | 13 | df = y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = \n| awards = \n| spouse = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| profession = Physician and epidemiologist\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Sotiris Tsiodras''' (born 1965) an [[Australia]]-born [[Greek people|Greek]] [[pathologist]] [[physician]], specializing in [[Infectious disease (medical specialty)|infectology]], in charge of [[Greece]]'s management of the [[coronavirus]] [[SARS-CoV-2]] [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Greece|crisis]].\n==Early years and education==\nTsiodras was born on 13 October 1965 in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]], into an [[immigrant]] family originating from [[Argolis|Neohori, Argolis]].<ref name=neohori>{{cite news  |date=22 March 2020 |title='\u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03b5\u03c5\u03c7\u03cc\u03bc\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5 \u03b3\u03b9\u03ac \u03c4\u03bf \u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03af \u03bc\u03b1\u03c2': \u039f\u03b9 \u03b3\u03bf\u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03cd \u03a3\u03c9\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b7 \u03a4\u03c3\u03b9\u03cc\u03b4\u03c1\u03b1 \u03bc\u03b9\u03bb\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd \u03b3\u03b9\u03ac \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03b3\u03b9\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2|url=https://www.arcadiaportal.gr/news/proseyhomaste-gia-paidi-mas-oi-goneis-toy-sotiri-tsiodra-sto-neohori-miloyn-gia-ton-gio-toys|language=Greek|trans-title='We are praying for our child': Sotiris Tsiodras' parents talks about their son|work=Arcadia portal |location= Greece|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> \nAfter the family moved back to Greece, he enrolled into the [[Ioannina]] medical school and then transferred to the [[National and Kapodistrian University of Athens|Athens University]] from which he graduated in March 1991 as a pathologist.<ref name=who>{{cite news  |date=6 April 2020 |title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u03a0\u03bf\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bf \u03bb\u03bf\u03b9\u03bc\u03c9\u03be\u03b9\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c9\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a4\u03c3\u03b9\u03cc\u03b4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03ba\u03ad\u03c1\u03b4\u03b9\u03c3\u03b5 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b5\u03bc\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c3\u03cd\u03bd\u03b7 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ae\u03bd\u03c9\u03bd|url=https://www.iefimerida.gr/ellada/koronoios-poios-einai-o-loimoxiologos-sotiris-tsiodras-poy-kerdise-tin-empistosyni-ton|language=Greek|trans-title=Coronavirus: Who is the Greek infectiologist who has won the trust of Greeks|workI Efimerida |location=Athens|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n==Medical career==\nTsiodras was appointed at the [https://401gsn.army.gr/ 401 Military Hospital] in 1993 where he served for one year. During the years 1994-1997, he worked as an internal medicine specialist specializing in [[Pathology]] at the [[Einstein Medical Center Philadelphia|Einstein Medical Center Philadelphia]] in the United States. From 1997 to 2001, he enrolled in the programs for [[infectious diseases]] at the [[Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center]] and [[Harvard Medical School]]. Between 1998 and 2001, he worked as a [[research fellow]] at the Harvard Medical School, from which, in June 2001, he received a [[Medical Sciences]] [[Master's Degree|M.A]].<ref name=studies>{{cite news  |date=24 March 2020 |title=Sydney-born immunologist Sotiris Tsiodras, the \u2018voice\u2019 of coronavirus in Greece|url=https://neoskosmos.com/en/161116/sydney-born-immunologist-sotiris-tsiodras-the-voice-of-coronavirus-in-greece/ |work=New World |location= Australia|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, he defended ''[[cum laude]]'' his [[doctoral dissertation]] at the Medical School of the National and Kapodistrian University of Athens.<ref name=dissertation>{{cite web |url=https://www.didaktorika.gr/eadd/handle/10442/13581|title=Effect of protease inhibitors on the metabolic syndrome of patients with HIV infection|last1=Tsiodras |first1=Sotiris |place= |publisher=[[National and Kapodistrian University of Athens]] |date=2003 |doi= 10.12681/eadd/13581|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Virus pandemic in Greece==\nIn 2019, the government appointed a group of experts to co-ordinate the state's management of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Greece|SARS-CoV-2 pandemic]] in Greece.<ref name=team>{{cite news  |date=3 March 2020 |title=\u039f\u03b4\u03b7\u03b3\u03af\u03b5\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03bb\u03bf\u03b9\u03bc\u03c9\u03be\u03b9\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03bf \u03a3\u03c9\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b7 \u03a4\u03c3\u03b9\u03cc\u03b4\u03c1\u03b1 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03b1 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03b5\u03c5\u03c0\u03b1\u03b8\u03ce\u03bd \u03bf\u03bc\u03ac\u03b4\u03c9\u03bd \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03ba\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc|language=Greek|trans-title=Directions from infectiologist Sotiris Tsiodras on the protection of vulnerable groups from the coronavirus|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.gr/entry/odeyies-loimoxiologow-tsiodras-prostasia-efpathon-omadon-koronoio_gr_5e5e4d99c5b67ed38b3885dd |work=[[Huffington Post]] |location=Athens |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> Tsiodras was appointed as the team's leader as well as the government's communications liaison for the health crisis.<ref name=appointment>{{cite news  |date=6 April 2020 |title='Nick Hard' and the soft-spoken professor keeping Greeks virus-safe |url=http://www.rfi.fr/en/wires/20200406-nick-hard-and-soft-spoken-professor-keeping-greeks-virus-safe |work=[[Radio France Internationale]] |location=Paris|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=heroes>{{cite news  |date=5 April 2020|last= Stevis-Gridneff|first= Matina|title=The Rising Heroes of the Coronavirus Era? Nations\u2019 Top Scientists|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/05/world/europe/scientists-coronavirus-heroes.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location= |url-access=subscription|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTsiodras is a practicing [[Eastern Orthodox|Orthodox Christian]], an aficionado of [[Byzantine]] [[hymnology]], and a member of his local-church's choir. He is married to Mina Tsiodras and they have seven children.<ref name=who/>\n==See also==\n*[[Cabinet of Kyriakos Mitsotakis|Greek government, post-2019 elections]]\n*[[Civil_service#Greece|Civil services of Greece]]\n*[[World Health Organisation]]\n*[[SARS]]\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.moh.gov.gr/ Greek Ministry of Health] official website (in [[Greek language|Greek]])\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tsiodras, Sotiris}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Greek people]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Greek descent]]\n", "name_user": "The Gnome", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sotiris_Tsiodras"}
{"title_page": "Markus Ziereis", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| fullname            = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1992|8|26}}\n| birth_place         = [[Roding, Germany|Roding]], Germany\n| height              = 1.85 m<ref name=\"kicker\" />\n| position            = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| currentclub         = [[TSV 1860 Munich|1860 Munich]]\n| clubnumber          = 24\n| youthyears1         = 1998\u20132005\n| youthclubs1         = SpVgg Neukirchen-Balbini\n| youthyears2         = 2005\u20132007\n| youthclubs2         = [[SSV Jahn Regensburg|Jahn Regensburg]]\n| youthyears3         = 2007\u20132010\n| youthclubs3         = [[TSV 1860 Munich|1860 Munich]]\n| years1              = 2010\u20132013\n| clubs1              = [[TSV 1860 Munich II|1860 Munich II]]\n| caps1               = 70\n| goals1              = 26\n| years2              = 2011\u20132013\n| clubs2              = [[TSV 1860 Munich|1860 Munich]]\n| caps2               = 4\n| goals2              = 0\n| years3              = 2013\u20132014\n| clubs3              = [[FSV Frankfurt]]\n| caps3               = 5\n| goals3              = 1\n| years4              = 2014\n| clubs4              = \u2192 [[SV Darmstadt 98|Darmstadt 98]] (loan)\n| caps4               = 6\n| goals4              = 0\n| years5              = 2014\n| clubs5              = [[Chemnitzer FC]]\n| caps5               = 21\n| goals5              = 0\n| years6              = 2015\u20132017\n| clubs6              = [[SSV Jahn Regensburg|Jahn Regensburg]]\n| caps6               = 41\n| goals6              = 19\n| years7              = 2017\u2013\n| clubs7              = [[TSV 1860 Munich|1860 Munich]]\n| caps7               = 50\n| goals7              = 15\n| nationalyears1      = 2007\u20132008\n| nationalteam1       = [[Germany national youth football team#Germany national under-16 squad|Germany U16]]\n| nationalcaps1       = 5\n| nationalgoals1      = 0\n| medaltemplates      = \n| club-update         = 15:27, 16 January 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''Markus Ziereis''' (born 26 August 1992) is a German professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for [[TSV 1860 Munich]].<ref name=\"kicker\">{{cite web | url = http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/regionalliga/rlby/regionalliga-bayern-2012/2017-18/1860-muenchen-5/43618/spieler_markus-ziereis.html | title = Markus Ziereis | language = de | website = kicker.de | access-date = 10 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nZiereis began his career with [[TSV 1860 Munich]] and made his [[2. Bundesliga]] debut for the club in November 2012, as a half-time substitute for [[Sebastian Maier]] in a 2\u20132 draw with [[1. FC Union Berlin]]. In 2013, he joined [[FSV Frankfurt]].<ref name=\"Jahn\">{{cite web | url = http://www.ssv-jahn.de/profis/news/2983 | title = Jahn holt Ziereis zur\u00fcck nach Hause | website = SSV Jahn Regensburg | date = 17 June 2015 | access-date = 25 July 2015}}</ref> In order to get more playing time, he was loaned to [[SV Darmstadt 98]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.fsv-frankfurt.de/cms/index.php?id=15&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=6958&cHash=6543211419de27ec4aa831b368f3f4df | title = FSV verleiht Markus Ziereis an Darmstadt 98 | language = German | publisher = FSV Frankfurt | date = 3 January 2014 | accessdate = 3 January 2014}}</ref> In 2014, he joined [[Chemnitzer FC]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.focus.de/regional/frankfurt-am-main/fussball-fussballer-ziereis-verlaesst-fsv-frankfurt-richtung-chemnitz_id_3952213.html | title = St\u00fcrmer Markus Ziereis wechselt vom Fu\u00dfball-Zweitligisten FSV Frankfurt zum Drittligisten Chemnitzer FC. | language = de | website = Focus Online | date = 27 June 2014 | access-date = 25 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter one season, he returned to [[SSV Jahn Regensburg]].<ref name=\"Jahn\" /> During the 2015\u201316 season he contributed 19 goals in 31 league matches to Regensburg's promotion from the [[Regionalliga Bayern]] to the [[3. Liga]].<ref name=\"1860munich\">{{cite news|title=Regensburgs Ziereis unterschreibt bei 1860|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/regionalliga/startseite/703624/artikel_regensburgs-ziereis-unterschreibt-bei-1860.html|accessdate=10 August 2017|work=kicker Online|date=10 August 2017|language=German}}</ref> His following season was blighted by injuries and he lost his place in the starting lineup, making just 10 substitute appearances.<ref name=\"1860munich\"/>\n\nOn 10 August 2017, Ziereis returned to 1860 Munich, thereby moving two tiers down, leaving newly promoted [[2. Bundesliga]] club Regensburg to play in the Regionalliga Bayern.<ref name=\"1860munich\"/>\n\n==International career==\nIn 2007 and 2008, Ziereis earned five caps for the Germany under-16 national team.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://datencenter.dfb.de/profil/224289 | title = Markus Ziereis | language = German | publisher = datencenter.dfb.de | accessdate = 10 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nZiereis is best friends with [[Kevin Volland]]. The duo shared a flat while playing together at [[TSV 1860 Munich]] as they both played for [[Bavarian Football Association]] youth teams.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Scharf|first1=J\u00fcrgen|title=Ziereis sorgt f\u00fcr Tore \u2013 und Stimmung|url=http://www.mittelbayerische.de/sport/regional/regensburg-nachrichten/ziereis-sorgt-fuer-tore-und-stimmung-21524-art1376754.html|accessdate=29 May 2016|work=[[Mittelbayerische Zeitung]]|date=10 May 2016|language=German}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Doppelpack: Wird Ziereis ein Kandidat f\u00fcr Maurer?|url=http://www.merkur.de/sport/amateur-fussball/landkreis-muenchen-stadt/doppelpack-wird-ziereis-kandidat-maurer-2527728.html|accessdate=29 May 2016|work=[[M\u00fcnchner Merkur]]|date=30 September 2012|language=German}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Leischwitz|first1=Christoph|title=In der Reifephase|url=http://www.sueddeutsche.de/muenchen/sport/tsv-muenchen-talente-in-der-reifephase-1.1017400|accessdate=29 May 2016|work=S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung|date=28 October 2010|language=German}}</ref> Volland was also witness when Ziereis married Evi Reiter on 28 December 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.mittelbayerische.de/region/regensburg-stadt-nachrichten/mz-moderatorin-evi-reiter-sagte-ja-21179-art1733986.html | title = MZ-Moderatorin Evi Reiter sagte Ja | trans-title = MZ moderator Evi Reiter said yes | language = de | website = Mittelbayerische Zeitung | date = 28 December 2018 | access-date = 28 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{Updated|match played 21 December 2019}}<ref>{{Soccerway|markus-ziereis/141841|access-date=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[DFB-Pokal]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[TSV 1860 Munich II|1860 Munich II]]\n|[[2010\u201311 Regionalliga#Regionalliga S\u00fcd|2010\u201311]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Regionalliga S\u00fcd (1994\u20132012)|Regionalliga S\u00fcd]]\n|10||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||10||0\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Regionalliga#Regionalliga S\u00fcd|2011\u201312]]\n|27||4||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||27||4\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 Regionalliga#Regionalliga Bayern|2012\u201313]]\n|[[Regionalliga Bayern]]\n|35||22||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||35||22\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!72!!26!!0!!0!!72!!26\n|-\n|[[TSV 1860 Munich|1860 Munich]]\n|[[2012\u201313 2. Bundesliga|2012\u201313]]\n|[[2. Bundesliga]]\n|4||0||0||0||4||0\n|-\n|[[FSV Frankfurt]]\n|[[2013\u201314 2. Bundesliga|2013\u201314]]\n|2. Bundesliga\n|5||1||0||0||5||1\n|-\n|[[SV Darmstadt 98|Darmstadt 98]] (loan)\n|[[2013\u201314 3. Liga|2013\u201314]]\n|[[3. Liga]]\n|6||0||0||0||6||0\n|-\